# Project Instructions

## Context

- **audience**: support engineering
- **language**: go
- **product**: escalation assistant
- **runtime**: cli

## Guidelines

# REST API Best Practices

When building REST endpoints:

## HTTP Methods
- Use GET for reading data (idempotent, no side effects)
- Use POST for creating new resources
- Use PUT for full updates of existing resources
- Use PATCH for partial updates
- Use DELETE for removing resources

## Status Codes
- Return 200 for successful GET, PUT, PATCH
- Return 201 for successful POST (resource created)
- Return 204 for successful DELETE (no content)
- Return 400 for bad requests (invalid input)
- Return 401 for authentication required
- Return 403 for forbidden (authenticated but not authorized)
- Return 404 for resource not found
- Return 500 for internal server errors

## Best Practices
- Include request IDs in headers for debugging and tracing
- Validate all inputs on the server side
- Use meaningful resource names (plural nouns)
- Version your API (e.g., /api/v1/resource)
- Return consistent error response format
- Use pagination for list endpoints
- Include rate limiting headers


# Testing Best Practices

## Test Structure
- Follow the Arrange-Act-Assert (AAA) pattern
- Write descriptive test names that explain what is being tested
- One assertion per test when possible
- Use setup and teardown methods to avoid duplication

## Test Coverage
- Write unit tests for individual functions and methods
- Write integration tests for component interactions
- Write end-to-end tests for critical user flows
- Aim for high coverage of business logic (80%+ recommended)

## Test Quality
- Tests should be deterministic (no flaky tests)
- Tests should be independent (can run in any order)
- Mock external dependencies (APIs, databases, file system)
- Use fixtures for test data
- Keep tests fast - slow tests won't get run

## Test-Driven Development
- Write tests before implementation when appropriate
- Red-Green-Refactor cycle
- Tests serve as living documentation


# Security Constraints

## Authentication & Authorization
- Never hardcode credentials, API keys, or secrets
- Use environment variables for sensitive configuration
- Implement proper authentication for all protected endpoints
- Use principle of least privilege for authorization
- Implement session timeout and token expiration

## Input Validation
- Validate and sanitize all user inputs
- Use parameterized queries to prevent SQL injection
- Escape output to prevent XSS attacks
- Validate file uploads (type, size, content)
- Implement rate limiting to prevent abuse

## Data Protection
- Encrypt sensitive data at rest
- Use TLS/HTTPS for data in transit
- Never log sensitive information (passwords, tokens, PII)
- Implement secure password hashing (bcrypt, argon2)
- Follow GDPR/privacy regulations for user data

## Error Handling
- Don't expose internal errors to users
- Log errors securely for debugging
- Use generic error messages for authentication failures
- Implement proper CORS policies


# Code Quality Standards

## Code Organization
- Follow the single responsibility principle
- Keep functions small and focused (< 50 lines recommended)
- Use meaningful variable and function names
- Organize code into logical modules/packages
- Avoid deep nesting (max 3-4 levels)

## Documentation
- Write clear docstrings for all public functions and classes
- Document complex algorithms and business logic
- Keep comments up-to-date with code changes
- Use type hints/annotations where supported

## Error Handling
- Implement comprehensive error handling
- Use specific exception types
- Provide helpful error messages
- Clean up resources properly (use context managers/finally blocks)
- Don't catch exceptions silently

## Code Style
- Follow language-specific style guides (PEP 8 for Python, etc.)
- Use consistent formatting (prefer automated formatters)
- Remove dead code and commented-out code
- Avoid magic numbers - use named constants
- Keep dependencies up-to-date

## Features

- **workflow_summary**: Summarize support escalation workflows in a human-readable document
- **launch_checklist**: Produce an implementation checklist before code generation begins

## Constraints

- No Hardcoded Secrets
- Comprehensive Test Coverage
- Clear Documentation
